04249nam a22006735i 9780292792630DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221996txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927926307 a10.7560/7519652doi  a(DE-B1597)586984  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1219.3.C2 ǂb M25 1997eb 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a529/.3/09721 aMalmström, Vincent H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCycles of the Sun, Mysteries of the Moon :bThe Calendar in Mesoamerican Civilization /cVincent H. Malmström. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2022] 4c©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Questions, Hypotheses, and Assorted Detours -- tChapter 2. Humans and Environment in the Americas -- tChapter 3. Strange Attraction: The Mystery of Magnetism -- tChapter 4. New Windows on the World: Working the Land and Sailing the Sea -- tChapter 5. The Olmec Dawning -- tChapter 6. The Long Count: Astronomical Precision -- tChapter 7. Calendar Reform and Eclipses: The Place of Edzna -- tChapter 8. The Golden Age -- tChapter 9. The Twilight of the Gods -- tChapter 10. Dawn in the Desert: The Rise of the Toltecs -- tChapter 11. People of the Pleiades: The Aztec Interlude -- tChapter 12. The Long Journey: A Retrospective -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe simple question "How did the Maya come up with a calendar that had only 260 days?" led Vincent Malmström to discover an unexpected "hearth" of Mesoamerican culture. In this boldly revisionist book, he sets forth his challenging, new view of the origin and diffusion of Mesoamerican calendrical systems—the intellectual achievement that gave rise to Mesoamerican civilization and culture. Malmström posits that the 260-day calendar marked the interval between passages of the sun at its zenith over Izapa, an ancient ceremonial center in the Soconusco region of Mexico's Pacific coastal plain. He goes on to show how the calendar developed by the Zoque people of the region in the fourteenth century B.C. gradually diffused through Mesoamerica into the so-called "Olmec metropolitan area" of the Gulf coast and beyond to the Maya in the east and to the plateau of Mexico in the west. These findings challenge our previous understanding of the origin and diffusion of Mesoamerican civilization. Sure to provoke lively debate in many quarters, this book will be important reading for all students of ancient Mesoamerica—anthropologists, archaeologists, archaeoastronomers, geographers, and the growing public fascinated by all things Maya.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aIndian astronomyzCentral America. 0aIndian astronomyzMexico. 0aIndian calendarzCentral America. 0aIndian calendarzMexico. 0aMaya astronomy. 0aMaya calendar. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75196540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292792630423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292792630/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK